04741nam a22005535i 9780773550216DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735502167 a10.1515/97807735502162doi  a(DE-B1597)657422  a(OCoLC)970406115  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPR3093b.S55 2017eb 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a791.43/62231 aSheppard, Philippa, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDevouring Time :bNostalgia in Contemporary Shakespearean Screen Adaptations /cPhilippa Sheppard. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource :b12 b&w photos  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures -- tAcknowledgments -- tRemembrance of Things Past -- tDefining Terms -- tWhy Shakespeare Films Now? -- tThe Drive to Realism in Shakespearean Adaptation to Film -- tRemembering Origins -- tShakespeare's Prologues on Page and Screen -- tNostalgia for the Stage in Shakespearean Films -- tDeath Rituals in Shakespeare, Almereyda, and Luhrmann -- tDisguise, Genre, and Play -- tGothic Aspects of Kenneth Branagh's Hamlet -- tArt and the Grotesque in Julie Taymor's Titus and Peter Greenaway's Prospero's Books -- tFive English Screen Directors' Approaches to Cross-Dressing in As You Like It and Twelfth Night -- tPropaganda and the Other in Branagh's Henry V and Fiennes's Coriolanus -- tMusic and Memory -- t“Sigh No More Ladies”: Shakespeare, Branagh, and Whedon Tackle Issues of Gender and Fidelity in Much Ado About Nothing -- t“O Mistress Mine”: Intercutting in Trevor Nunn's Twelfth Night -- tNostalgia in Hoffman's William Shakespeare's A Midsummer Night's Dream and Branagh's Love's Labour's Lost -- tAriel's Singing Body as Interpreted by Greenaway and Taymor -- tConclusion -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFrom Kenneth Branagh’s groundbreaking Henry V to Justin Kurzel’s haunting Macbeth, many modern filmmakers have adapted Shakespeare for the big screen. Their translations of Renaissance plays to modern cinema both highlight and comment on contemporary culture and attitudes to art, identity, and the past. A dynamic analysis of twenty-seven films adapted from Shakespeare’s works, Philippa Sheppard’s Devouring Time addresses a wide range of topics, including gender, ritual, music, setting, rhetoric, and editing. She argues that the directors’ choice to adapt these four-hundred-year-old plays is an act of nostalgia, not only for the plays themselves, but also for the period in which they were written, the association of genius that accompanies them, and the medium of theatre. Sheppard contends that millennial anxiety brought on by the social and technological revolutions of the last five decades has generated a yearning for Shakespeare because he is an icon of a literary culture that is often deemed threatened. Authoritative and accessible, Devouring Time’s investigations of filmmakers’ nostalgia for the art of the past shed light on Western concepts of gender, identity, and colonialism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish dramaxFilm adaptations. 0aFilm adaptationsxHistory and criticism. 0aMotion pictures and literature. 0aNostalgia in motion pictures. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077355021640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773550216423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/docum